          title: "How Governments View Cryptocurrency",
          content:
            '<h2><strong>8. How Governments View Cryptocurrency</strong></h2><p>Different countries have different rules:</p><ul><li><strong>United States:</strong> Crypto is legal but regulated as a digital asset.<br><br></li><li><strong>India:</strong> Legal to trade but taxed under income rules.<br><br></li><li><strong>UAE:</strong> Encouraging blockchain innovation with licensed exchanges.<br><br></li><li><strong>El Salvador:</strong> Bitcoin is an official legal tender.<br><br></li></ul><p>Global organizations like the <a href="https://www.imf.org/en/home" target="_blank"><strong>IMF</strong></a> are studying how digital currencies can coexist with traditional systems.</p><p><strong>10. The Future of Cryptocurrency</strong></p><p>The crypto world is expanding beyond trading. It’s now part of <strong>AI, gaming, finance, and metaverse ecosystems</strong>.</p><h3><strong>a) Integration with AI and DeFi</strong></h3><p>AI-driven trading bots, DeFi platforms, and smart contracts are changing how finance works.</p><h3><strong>b) Central Bank Digital Currencies (CBDCs)</strong></h3><p>Governments are creating their own digital versions of money - like <strong>India’s Digital Rupee</strong> and <strong>China’s Digital Yuan</strong>.</p><h3><strong>c) Wider Adoption</strong></h3><p>Analysts from <a href="https://legal.pwc.de/content/services/global-crypto-regulation-report/pwc-global-crypto-regulation-report-2025.pdf" target="_blank"><strong>PwC</strong></a> predict that by <strong>2030</strong>, digital assets will become a key part of global financial systems.</p>',
