            '<h2><strong>Pros and Cons of Joining a Presale</strong></h2><h3><strong>Pros</strong></h3><ul><li>Early entry before public trading.<br><br></li><li>Lower price compared to post-launch.<br><br></li><li>Helps learn how blockchain funding works.<br><br></li></ul><h3><strong>Cons</strong></h3><ul><li>High-risk if the project fails or delays launch.<br><br></li><li>Scams exist, so verifying contract addresses is essential.<br><br></li><li>Tokens may have vesting periods before full access.<br><br></li></ul><p>Presales can be exciting but should always be approached with research and patience.</p><h2><strong>What to Check Before Joining</strong></h2><p>A few checks make a big difference for beginners:</p><ul><li><strong>Official contract address:</strong> Verify it on Etherscan or BSCScan.<br><br></li><li><strong>Smart-contract audit:</strong> Look for audits by trusted firms like <a href="https://www.certik.com/">CertiK</a> or <a href="https://hacken.io/">Hacken</a>.<br><br></li><li><strong>Transparency:</strong> Confirm the team, roadmap, and tokenomics are public.<br><br></li><li><strong>Community:</strong> Healthy, active discussion groups usually signal authenticity.<br><br></li></ul><h2><strong>A Real-World Example</strong></h2><p>Some platforms combine transparency, KYC verification, and tokenised access for presales.</p><p>For instance, <a href="/"><strong>IPO Genie</strong></a> runs AI-driven token offerings where every participant is verified before joining, and token ownership is recorded directly on the blockchain.</p>',
